postcontent:
This Smith is in good condition with no scratches or dings. I have included a write-up of the model 65-3. 

The Smith and Wesson model 65 revolver was introduced in 1973. It was one of several .357 magnum variations of the extremely popular model 10. It is built on the medium sized K frame, making it one of Smith and Wesson's medium-weight models. 

The model 65 was produced from 1973 to 1999, then some minor changes were made. It continued to be produced until 2004. 

The model 65 was always a popular gun with law enforcement officers, as it could handle full-power .357 magnum or .38 +P loads without a problem, and had very good balance and handling characteristics.

The model 65 is no longer produced, While it's not a collectors item (yet), it is a very desirable revolver.

postcontent:
Ruger P-94 .40 S&W 

The P-Series are short recoil–operated, locked breech semi-automatic pistols. It utilizes a SIG P220 type locking system, and an M1911-style tilting barrel.

It has an ambidextrous manual safety/decocker located on the slide; when the safety lever is lowered to the safe position, the firing pin is cammed into the slide away from the hammer, the trigger is disconnected from the sear and the hammer is decocked. The decocker models have no manual safety; instead, when the lever is lowered it only cams the firing pin into the slide and drops the hammer. When the lever is released the firing pin springs back to the normal position. It features an automatic firing pin safety that blocks the firing pin unless the trigger is pulled fully rearward.

Constructed of investment cast parts and proprietary Ruger alloys. Nearly all internal parts, including the barrel, are stainless steel; while the slide and ejector are carbon steel. 

It uses double-column box magazine and has a 10 round capacity.The P-Series pistols have an ambidextrous magazine release located behind the trigger guard, it can be pushed forward from either side to eject the magazine.

postcontent: Roy Dunlap Custom Pre-64 Winchester Model 70 Long Range Match rifle chambered in 30-338. An absolutely Beautiful rifle by a Master Rifle builder. The rifle is in magnificent condition and has been fired very little. I have owned it for over 25 years and have only fired it twice, I have fired about 100 rounds of ammunition through it. The bore is about mirror bright and very nice. The stock is just gorgeous with beautiful figure and cross grain, real exhibition quality wood. I was told that it is not walnut but is Myrtle wood. This may be the most beautiful rifle ever made by Mr. Dunlop. I know that I have never seen a picture of a more beautiful rifle made by him. There are no cracks or repairs of any kind and only a very few light handling marks and dings. It is equipped with the original Roy F. Dunlop Sure-Grip White Line butt pad and is so marked. The metal retains about 99 plus percent of the original blue and shows little if any wear. The barrel is 28 inches long. The chamber end measures 1.150 inches and the muzzle is .880 inches. It has a 1 in 12 inch twist rate and is 6 groove. It is equipped with a Redfield Palma rear Micrometer sight and a Redfield International Match front globe sight. The rifle weights 13 lbs. 6 oz. with the sights mounted. For those of you that don't know anything about Roy Dunlop I found the following on a website. "Roy Dunlap, arguably, was one of the greatest gunsmiths of the 20 century. Roy Dunlap learned gunsmithing as an individual machinist and during World War II he was a sergeant and field armorer for the ordnance department. Shortly after the war he wrote his first book entitled Ordnance Went Up Front. However, he is most famous for his 714 page book "Gunsmithing" which was first published in 1950 and has been republished a dozen times or more since. Gunsmithing, a highly rated piece of gunning literature, praised as a well written with an abundance of information of great detail. It has been long considered a must for the experienced gunsmith and small arms designer. Roy Dunlap custom rifles are extremely scarce and are rarely offered for sale, so don’t miss out on your chance to own this beautiful rifle by one of America’s premier gunsmiths." I took loads of pictures for you to look at. If you have any additional questions please feel free to email me. This may well be the nicest looking Roy Dunlop rifle you will ever see or have an opportunity to own.
